ca.ualberta.cs.drivr

Class ElasticSearch

  • java.lang.Object
    • ca.ualberta.cs.drivr.ElasticSearch

  • public class ElasticSearch
extends java.lang.Object
    In ElasticSearch, we store two classes: Requests and Users. For Users, you can add, update and search for a user. For a request, you can add and update a request. You can also search for a request, either by getting all requests with a specific keyword, all requests within a specified geolocation or all requests associated to that user. This class, while handling all calls to the ElasticSearchController, also handles all cases where the user goes offline by storing the info they gave and then uploading it to ElasticSearch when they get connected to the internet again.
    See Also:
    ElasticSearchController, MainActivity

      • saveRequest

        public void saveRequest(Request request)
        Here, the request is saved by first checking if there's anything made offline that needs to be saved, then seeing if the user is online. If they are, then we add the request in ElasticSearch. Else, we add it into requestsMadeOffline and offlineRequests and set newInfo to true.
        Parameters:
        request - The request to be saved in ElasticSearch.

      • updateRequest

        public void updateRequest(Request request)
        Here, the request is updated by first checking if there's anything made offline that needs to be saved, then seeing if the user is online. If they are, then we update the request in ElasticSearch. Else, we add it into offlineUpdateRequest and offlineRequests and set newInfo to true.
        Parameters:
        request - The request to be updated in ElasticSearch.

      • loadUserRequests

        public java.util.ArrayList<Request> loadUserRequests(java.lang.String username)
        Here, the requests for a user are gotten by first checking if there's anything made offline that needs to be saved, then if the user is online it will get the requests associated to the given username, store them in offlineRequests if successful and return it. Else, if the search was unsuccessful, or the user is offline, it'll just return the previously stored requests.
        Parameters:
        username - The username of the user.
        Returns:
        The ArrayList of matching requests

      • searchRequestByGeolocation

        public java.util.ArrayList<Request> searchRequestByGeolocation(android.location.Location geolocation)
        Here, the requests for a user are gotten by first checking if there's anything made offline that needs to be saved, then if the user is online it will get the requests within 50km of the given geolocation and return the results gotten if successful. Else, if the search was unsuccessful, or the user is offline, it'll return null.
        Parameters:
        geolocation - The location given by the user.
        Returns:
        The ArrayList of matching requests

      • searchRequestByKeyword

      • saveUser

        public boolean saveUser(User user)
        Here, the requests for a given keyword are gotten by first checking if there's anything offline that needs to be saved. Next, if the user is connected to the internet, it will first check to see if the username already exists in ElasticSearch by using GetUser in the controller and then storing it. If the user returned by the serach is null, then it'll save the user given by the user in ElasticSearch and return true. Else, if the username's already stored in ElasticSearch, or the user is offline, it'll return false, with the app saving the user's info for when they come back online. Returning a boolean is necessary since we shouldn't allow user to initially get into the app unless their user info is in ElasticSearch.
        Parameters:
        user - The user to be stored in ElasticSearch.
        Returns:
        True or False to indicate the state

      • updateUser
